		<header>
			
			<h1>Trade policy: Decline in Senegalâ€™s regional exports</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Senegalâ€™s exports to West Africa dropped by 9.64% between 2008 and 2009, from CFAfr397.3 billion to CFAfr 359 billion. In a conference in Dakar on 8 September 2010 to promote regional trade, hosted by Senegalâ€™s National Council of Employers (CNP), Madior Bouna Niang, the head of CNPâ€™s Customs and Trade Facilitation Unit, called on the participants to take the news of the fall in Senegalese exports as a wake-up call for diversification and consolidation of Senegalese exports to regional markets. Among other factors, conference participants linked the fall in regional exports to the process of preparing for the tariff dismantlement to be undertaken in West African countries in preparation for the implementation of the regional EPA with EU. </p><p>The importance of developing a regional export strategy to complement regional transport infrastructure development initiatives was stressed by Hamidou Diop, Secretary-General of CNP. Participants at the conference called on the government of Senegal to support the national agri-business sector in undertaking the production and trade adjustments necessary to ensure competitiveness in regional markets in the face of the wider trade liberalisation processes under way, particular as part of the EPA process. </p><p>ENDA-Third World organised a similar conference a month earlier in Dakar to discuss the problem of food security in the region. Conference participants from across the region emphasised the importance of proper land management for the development of the smallholder farming sector. Although smallholder farming contributes approximately 50% of GDP in Senegal and some other countries in the region, more than 70% of these smallholder farmers receive no form of support for the proper management of their land resources. At the end of the conference most participants were of the view that for smallholder farming to be sustainable in Senegal and beyond, the government will, among other things, need to provide appropriate support to the smallholder farming sector, including access to pesticides and fertilisers. </p>
		
		
