				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>So far only CÃ´te dâ€™Ivoire and Ghana have concluded an IEPA in West Africa. In parallel to the EU-ECOWAS negotiations on a regional EPA, efforts are under way to bring West African governmentsâ€™ policies to a â€˜common starting lineâ€™ for EPA implementation, through the establishment of a genuinely common external tariff among those West African countries that are committed to regional trade integration initiatives. It is this process that is throwing issues of competitiveness at national level into stark focus. This accounts for the growing concern over the need for effective pump-priming support to production-and trade-adjustment processes (including modernisation and diversification) across the region.</p><p>Nowhere is this need greater than in the sphere of smallholder agricultural production, where problems of indebtedness, input supply and the vast inequalities in the distribution of commercial power along supply chains, serve to leave the sector poorly placed to compete in a liberalised trading environment.</p><p>In recent years, the government of Senegal has tried to improve the agricultural production through the National Agricultural Investment Programme (PNIA), with the development of value-added processing within better functioning supply chains being seen as the key to improving the livelihood of smallholder farmers. Recently, building on the example of Canada, President Wade has created a Green Bank with an amount of 30 billion CFA francs dedicated to peasant farmers. Although at present the farmers own only 10% of the shares of the Green Bank, it is hoped that smallholder farmers will eventually own the majority of shares. </p><p>Addressing financing issues is undoubtedly one part of the challenge of preparing the basis for agricultural innovation and modernisation. A second major part of the challenge will be improving the functioning of the supply chain and helping farmers to secure better access to remunerative markets.</p>
